For the same email-security vendor products, supply a public commercial-availability source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL).

A public commercial-availability source must expose a concrete commercial term for the named product: a named plan, package, SKU, public price or rate, free or paid tier, trial terms, purchasable listing, procurement or transaction context, or explicitly commercial packaging.

A valid `vendor_product` is a real public email-security product, service, suite, or product module for protecting email, mailbox, collaboration, or messaging environments from phishing, BEC, malware, ransomware, impersonation, account-takeover, spam, or comparable email-borne threats. Generic vendor or platform pages count only when the page ties the commercial surface to the named product or module. For a module-level product, suite-level commercial evidence can count only when the page explicitly presents the module as part of that suite and the commercial term applies to the suite including that module; suite-only evidence does not support a separately named module when the page names only the suite/platform, another module, or a generic vendor package.

The cited page must be an official vendor page, first-party marketplace page, or clearly authorized commercial listing surface. Third-party pricing-estimate aggregators and lead-generation cost pages are out of scope.

Requirements:

- The page must clearly identify the named vendor and product.
- The page should make the eligible commercial source role visible: official vendor ownership, first-party marketplace context, or clearly authorized seller/listing context.
- The page must expose a concrete public commercial term for the product: a named plan, package, SKU, public price or rate, free or paid tier, trial terms, purchasable listing, procurement or transaction context, or explicitly commercial packaging. A bare marketplace card, category page, app-install shell, generic product page, or contact-sales page without such a term is not enough.
